It was asked to create the method `add`. I rephrase what it needs to do: it should take a Circle instance as argument, and then mutate the current Circle instance so its surface has now to the other&#39;s surface added to it.

If we perform that action as a math&#39;s exercise we could say we have two circles defined by their radi: &#119903;&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; and &#119903;&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;

The surface of the first circle is &#119904;&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; and it can be calculated from its radius as:

&#119904;&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = π&#119903;&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;&#178;

And the second circle has a surface of:

&#119904;&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; = π&#119903;&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;&#178;

Now we want to calculate a third radius (&#119903;&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt;) such that the corresponding surface &#119904;&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt; is the sum of the two original surfaces, i.e. &#119904;&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; + &#119904;&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;. So we need to solve these equations:

1. &#119904;&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; = π&#119903;&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;&#178;
2. &#119904;&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; = π&#119903;&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;&#178;
3. &#119904;&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt; = π&#119903;&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt;&#178;
4. &#119904;&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt; = &#119904;&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; + &#119904;&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;

Given are: &#119903;&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; and &#119903;&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;, and asked is &#119903;&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt;.

So let&#39;s solve that:

If in equality (4) we substitute all &#119904;&lt;sub&gt;&#119894;&lt;/sub&gt;, using the other three equalities, we derive:

π&#119903;&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt;&#178; = π&#119903;&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;&#178; + π&#119903;&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;&#178;

...which reduces to:

&#119903;&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt;&#178; = &#119903;&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;&#178; + &#119903;&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;&#178;

...which reduces to:

&#119903;&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt; = √(&#119903;&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;&#178; + &#119903;&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;&#178;)

The code does this in a bit overkill way, as the involvement of `PI` is not needed, but OK, it&#39;s what this code is doing.

